 HN13[
] Courts use the terms "contract" "combination" and "conspiracy" interchangeably to describe an agreement between 
two or more actors to restrain trade. Todorov v. DCH Healthcare Auth., 921 F.2d 1438, 1455 (11th Cir. 1991).

 HN26[
] The elements of monopolization are 1) possession of monopoly power; and 2) the acquisition, use, or maintenance 
of that power for anticompetitive or predatory purposes. Aspen Skiing Co., 472 U.S. at 595-96. HN27[
] The elements of attempted monopolization are 1) defendant has engaged in predatory or anticompetitive conduct, 2) 
with the specific intent to monopolize, and 3) there is a dangerous probability defendant will achieve monopoly power. Spectrum 
Sports, 506 U.S. at 456.

 The court observes that HN19[
] Rule 9(b) does not place a heavy burden on plaintiffs, given that Rule 9 must be read in conjunction with the relatively liberal pleading requirements of Rule 8. See Shahmirzadi v. Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co., 
636 F. Supp. 49, 53 (D.D.C. 1985).

 HN10[
] The Cable Act preempts and supercedes state law only when it is "inconsistent" with the Act, "a statutory formulation which suggests that state law not inconsistent with the Cable Act is not pre-empted." 47 U.S.C. Â§ 556(c); Cablevision of Boston 
Ltd. P'ship v. Flynn, 710 F. Supp. 23, 28 (D. Mass 1989).

 HN36[
] As applied in antitrust law, the continuing violations doctrine allows a plaintiff to recover for anti-competitive conduct that would ordinarily be time-barred as long as the conduct represents an ongoing unlawful practice that includes violations 
within the limitations period. See 2 Phillip E. Areeda & Herbert Hovenkamp, Antitrust Law P320c (2d ed. 2002).

 HN3[
] Private persons are given a cause of action under the Sherman Act by Section 4 of the Clayton Act, which provides for a suit to recover treble damages by any person injured in his business or property by the violation of the antitrust laws. Section 
16 of the Clayton Act allows injured parties to sue for injunctive relief.

 HN3[
] "Resale" is a legally-prescribed method of opening local telecommunications markets to competition whereby 
competing companies (or resellers) purchase the incumbent companies' retail telecommunications services at wholesale prices

